\begin_layout Section
Learning outcomes you are expected to achieve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Econ 460 students are expected to show proficiency in the following by the
 end of the course (The numbers in parenthesis are the Pepall et al.
 sections that cover this topics).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Students should recognize the relationship between technology, costs and
 the firm's optimizing behavior (lecture notes will be provided).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Quotation
Topics: cost function, economies of scale, sunk cost, long run, short run.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Students should acquire a fundamental knowledge of the problems faced by
 different types of monopolies (5.1 to 5.4.
 6.1 and 6.2 7.1 to 7.3)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Quotation
Topics: monopoly, natural monopoly, multi-plant monopoly, monopoly selling
 in several markets, horizontal and vertical differentiation, price discriminati
on 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Students should acquire an understanding of how firms make choices under
 strategic interaction (9.1 to 9.5; 10.1 and 10.2; 11.1).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Quotation
Topics: static games, dominated strategies, Nash equilibrium, Cournot, Bertrand,
 Stackelberg, Hotelling's model.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Students should understand the basics of anti-competitive behavior (lecture
 notes and 15.1, 1.5 and 15.4).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Quotation
Topics: collusion and merger.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
